 What We are Watching

 Theatre: Myths, heroes and the common man 

 Kolkatar Elektra

 Swapna Sandhani stages Buddhadeb Bose?s Kolkatar Elektra, an adaptation from the Oresteian legends of Elektra. Director Koushik Sen juxtaposes the Greek setting against the present-day war scenario. While actress Sudipa Basu plays Elektra in contemporary Calcutta, Sen?s wife Reshmi slips into the Hellenic heroine?s role.

 Catch it at Sujata Sadan, 6.30 pm, on May 21

 Bappaditya

 Nandikar presents Abanindranath Tagore?s popular story about a village boy?s transformation into a king. The production features Sohini Sengupta flitting in and out of five characters ? Bappaditya, the three women he is enamoured of and the narrator. Directed by Goutam Halder.

 Catch it at Rabindra Sadan, 6.30 pm, on May 21

 Shodh-Bodh

 The play by Rabindranath Tagore is a satirical take on Bengali society imitating a Western way of life. The production by Anya Theatre looks at the ups and downs in the romantic fortunes of a youth. Directed by Bibhas Chakraborty. 

 Catch it at Academy of Fine Arts, 6.30 pm, on May 22 

 Sateroi July

 With the Godhra riots as the backdrop, the Ganakrishti production is a terse commentary on communal tensions fanned by people with a political agenda. Directed by Bratya Basu.

 Catch it at Academy of Fine Arts, 6.30 pm, on May 24




